{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Relational Databases (SQL) vs NoSQL Databases\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1. Relational Databases (SQL)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Definition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Relational databases store data in tables (rows and columns) with a predefined schema that ensures data consistency. Data relationships are enforced using primary and foreign keys, and data is accessed through Structured Query Language (SQL). Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, Microsoft SQL Server.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Advantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Data Integrity and Accuracy (ACID Compliance)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ensures reliable transactions using Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ideal for applications handling money transfers, inventory tracking, and record management.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Structured Query Language (SQL)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab SQL provides a standard and powerful way to perform complex queries, joins, and aggregations efficiently.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Strong Data Relationships\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Designed to manage interrelated data; excellent for use cases with multiple table dependencies.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Data Validation and Constraints\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Enforces strict data types, unique keys, and relationships that maintain quality and prevent anomalies.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Mature Ecosystem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Long history of use with extensive documentation, community support, and trusted performance optimization tools.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Disadvantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Limited Scalability\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Primarily scales vertically (by upgrading hardware), not horizontally across multiple servers.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Schema Rigidity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Altering the schema often requires redesigning tables, which can lead to downtime in production systems.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Reduced Performance on Big or Complex Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Complex joins and heavy write loads reduce performance in large-scale environments.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Not Ideal for Unstructured Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Suited mainly for structured, tabular data; struggles with unstructured formats like JSON or images.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2. NoSQL Databases\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Definition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"NoSQL\u8221" stands for Not Only SQL. These databases don\u8217't rely on a fixed schema and can handle unstructured, semi-structured, or polymorphic data. They come in various types \u8212- key-value stores, document-based, graph-based, and columnar. Examples: MongoDB, Cassandra, DynamoDB, Redis, Neo4j.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Advantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab High Scalability (Horizontal Scaling)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Designed for easy data distribution across servers and data centers.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Flexible Schema\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Schema-less structures allow quick adjustments as data requirements evolve.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Performance and Speed\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Optimized for high-speed read and write operations.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Support for Unstructured and Semi-Structured Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Can store JSON, documents, graphs, and multimedia directly.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Fault Tolerance and High Availability\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Built-in replication and partitioning ensure minimal downtime and data resilience.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Disadvantages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Eventual Consistency (BASE Model)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Data may take time to synchronize across nodes.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab No Standard Query Language\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Each NoSQL database has its own query methods or APIs, requiring unique expertise.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Limited Relationship Handling\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Complex relationships and joins are managed at the application level.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Data Duplication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Denormalized data improves speed but can lead to redundancy.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Less Mature Ecosystem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Tools and standards are less established compared to traditional SQL systems.\sa180\sa180\par}
