{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4. When to Use Each\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Use Relational Databases (SQL) when:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You need reliable transactions and consistency.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The data structure is stable and well-defined.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your system relies heavily on data relationships. Examples: Banking systems, accounting, enterprise apps.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Use NoSQL Databases when:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You manage large-scale, evolving, or unstructured data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You need fast access and distributed scalability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Rapid development and flexibility matter more than strict consistency. Examples: E-commerce personalization, social media data, IoT analytics.\sa180\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Summary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Relational Databases: precision, structure, and reliability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab NoSQL Databases: speed, scalability, and flexibility.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Modern systems often combine both (polyglot persistence) to get the best of each.\sa180\par}
